  "text": "Specifications of technical systems consists of many requirements written in natural language, usually English. These requirements are typically expressed by means of one sentence and can be categorized into low-level requirements and highlevel requirements. Low-level requirements can easily be translated into formal counterparts, because they are very precise and usually refer to specific signals of the design and concrete values. High-level requirements on the other hand need further investigation of the context that can be obtained from reading the specification and hence a direct translation is often not possible. Problem 2 (Requirements classification [CITATION_1] ): Given a set of requirements in natural language text R = {R 1 , . . . , R n }, the requirements classification problem asks to find a partition (L, H) of S such that L consists of all low-level requirements and H consists of all high-level requirements. The low-level requirements are further partitioned into clusters {C 1 , . . . , C k } that contain similar sentences. That means that all sentences in one cluster can be automatically translated into a canonical form that is described by a representative of the cluster. This representative also consists of variables and hence can be used for describing the automatic translation of the low-level requirements of the cluster into formal assertions.",
